SIMPLE: pressure
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pressure
<hw>Pres"sure</hw> <pr>(?; 138)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF., fr. L.
<ets>pressura</ets>, fr. <ets>premere</ets>. See 4th
<er>Press</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of pressing, or the
condition of being pressed; compression; a squeezing; a crushing;
<as>as, a <ex>pressure</ex> of the hand</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A contrasting force or impulse of any kind; <as>as,
the <ex>pressure</ex> of poverty; the <ex>pressure</ex> of taxes; the
<ex>pressure</ex> of motives on the mind; the <ex>pressure</ex> of
civilization.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where the <qex>pressure</qex> of danger was not felt.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Affliction; distress; grievance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My people's <qex>pressures</qex> are grievous.</q> <rj><qau>Eikon
Basilike.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the midst of his great troubles and <qex>pressures</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Urgency; <as>as, the <ex>pressure</ex> of
business</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Impression; stamp; character impressed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All saws of books, all forms, all <qex>pressures</qex> past.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>The action of a force against
some obstacle or opposing force; a force in the nature of a thrust,
distributed over a surface, often estimated with reference to the amount
upon a unit's area.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Electro-motive force.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Atmospheric pressure</b></col>, <col><b>Center of
pressure</b></col>, etc.</mcol> <cd>See under <er>Atmospheric</er>,
<er>Center</er>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Back pressure</b></col>
<fld>(Steam engine)</fld>, <cd>pressure which resists the motion of the
piston, as the pressure of exhaust steam which does not find free
outlet.</cd> -- <col><b>Fluid pressure</b></col>, <cd>pressure like that
exerted by a fluid. It is a thrust which is normal and equally intense
in all directions around a point.</cd> <au>Rankine.</au> --
<col><b>Pressure gauge</b></col>, <cd>a gauge for indicating fluid
pressure; a manometer.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pressure cooker</ent>⟦br⟧
